<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="a88a3185977d9799c4ba70b1055ab086" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Standard format - a player/collector's view<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.42)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14238'>Slobodan "olorin_hr1" Obrenovic</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14238&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 28, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> First of all, I would like to state that I have been collecting LOTR cards since the game appeared in Croatia and have played the game and actively participated in tournaments for almost a year. I am a semi-serious player, I play in tournaments whenever I am able to. I especially enjoy large tournaments, with a variety of different decks and people. I also play casually for at least ten hours a week, which makes me a LOTR tcg addict. I am a serious collector and trader and have spent a lot of money on my different decks (that I usually lend to other players) and my collection of foils of which I am very proud of. <br />
<br />
I have always considered LOTR a very balanced game, where the slight imbalances were easily countered by the shifts in metagame. The system of balancing the game by issuing new cards that counter the strategy that is considered too strong and errating the cards was next to perfect from not only my viewpoint, but from the viewpoint of the overwhelming majority of my LOTR-playing friends (from the fun to the pro level). <br />
<br />
Enter the Standard format. &quot;Standard format is a PREFERRED format for the tournament play&quot;. It seems to me that in a while the Standard format will become MANDATORY for the tournament play. That&#39;ll be the day I&#39;ll quit playing the tournaments. And I have never played an Uruk/Gondor choke deck (although I have it, but I lend it to others), so my complaints are not based on that. <br />
<br />
As a serious collector, I have spent a lot of time and money buying and trading for the cards that are banned in a new format, including their foil versions. I have never intended to sell my collection, but was aware of its market value (and play value). Now that the cards are being banned, their market value will plunge and I feel as if I was robbed (since the cards cannot be played and aren&#39;t worth the money I invested in them). I am horryfied and outraged by the prospect that more cards could and will be banned in the future. <br />
<br />
I come from Croatia, a nation wher the standard of living is low, and an average player is a high school or a college student with very little money to spend. About 50% of Croatian players play an Uruk-hai deck in one form or another. 99.9% of Croatian players have at least one banned card in their decks. Now the hundreds of dollars that they have spent on their decks, a sum that is not easy to come by for an average Croatian player, might have as well been set on fire. Now the player faces two choices: one - to spend another few hundreds of dollars for buying cards for a new deck, hoping that these cards will not be banned and two - to stop participating in tournaments. For me the choice is obvious. <br />
<br />
Although Decipher&#39;s aim was probably balancing the game, the end result will be counterproductive, as I will show later. For now, let me focus on the particular cards: <br />
<br />
1R40 Elrond, Lord of Rivendell <br />
1R45 Galadriel, Lady of Light <br />
1R80 Ottar, Man of Laketown <br />
Here comes the new buzzword, &quot;cultural enforcement&quot;. The thing I don&#39;t like in American society and its influence on the English language are empty phrases like &quot;politically correct&quot;, &quot;culturally biased&quot; and similar bs. &quot;Cultural enforcement&quot; is one of them. Elrond says: To play, spot Gandalf or an Elf. Isn&#39;t that enough of a &quot;cultural enforcement&quot;? Have you read the LOTR book? Elrond is a character that represents high-elven wisdom and helps the members of all the Middle-Earth&#39;s races on their quests. The similar goes for Galadriel. She is very powerful and wise, and as such the card should have a strong ability. She has helped all the members of the Fellowship with her gift and advice. Why should she be &quot;c.e.&quot;? Ottar - Gandalf culture, to play, spot Gandalf. What should be his cultural enforcement, to play, spot two Gandalves and exert one of them??? About their card drawing ability, the rule of 4, combined with their high twilight cost was enough. In Croatian play environment, nobody played Shoulder to shoulder decks, because there are a number of shadow strategies that can stop them. Very few people played that Elrond and were not particularly successful. Only some Gandalf decks (rarely played in Croatia) played Ottar. Only Galadriel was the essential part of all Last Alliance decks. These decks were strong, but not invincible (I take them out regularly with my Moria swarm, Saruman&#39;s Power discards Last Alliance, Grima works against those decks etc.). <br />
<br />
1R139 Savagery to Match Their Numbers <br />
3R68 Saruman, Keeper of Isengard <br />
4C192 Uruk Regular <br />
Uruk-hai were always the strongest Shadow culture in the game. However, the edge they had was countered by the metagame i.e. the induction of anti-Uruk cards. My Gandalf/Gondor deck includes heavy twilight denial, betrayals, defend it and hope - s, aragorn&#39;s bow, etc. and rarely loses against the Uruk Bomb. The great advantage for the Uruk&#39;s is Saruman&#39;s Power. In reality, none of these three cards alone is too strong, but all three combined with Saruman&#39;s Power represent the ultimate shadow combo in the game. Savagery was the necessary card to counter different nine companion fellowships. Without it, the FP player may put all nine on the table aginst the Uruk-hai and run like, well, like the Uruk-hai are on his tail. Saruman was also excellent at stopping and punishing the large fellowships - having 4 fierce minions on the table against nine unequipped companions results in multiple casualties on the FP side. It is worth remembering that in the book Saruman is a mighty wizard of the order of Istari. He is a Maia and one of the three most powerful beings in Middle-earth (Sauron, Saruman, Gandalf) and is also the mightiest minion that personally faces the fellowship (since Sauron never leaves Barad-dur). As such, he should be a super card, as he is. Uruk regular is too strong to be a common. It should have been a rare. If I was forced to chose one of the three above mentioned cards to be errated, my choice would be a regular - I would make it a unique minion (that is if I was forced to choose between those three, I think that the best option is to leave them as they are). <br />
<br />
1U234 Ulaire Nertea <br />
Again &quot;Cultural whatever&quot;. For me , Nertea simulates the situation that didn&#39;t appear in the book, but is possible in the Tolkien&#39;s world (as many of the cards do) - the fellowship running from the Nazgul encounters the ambush of the Orc Swarm. Now that Nertea is banned, Moria swarm has only one way of beating a large fellowship, and that is Enquea, which can and will be countered by common Eowyn and will kill at most two out of nine companions and it too lacks cultural enforcement. <br />
<br />
1C248 Forces of Mordor <br />
Just as the Sauron swarm possibility was added to the game by the BOHD cards, it has been taken away by this move. I&#39;ll have to see how it functions in the play environment before I say more. If proven too strong, the card should have been errated, not banned. <br />
<br />
1R313 Sting <br />
Come on, it&#39;s the Sting. The Decipher design team has again shown the total disregard for the Tolkien&#39;s masterpiece. Sting is essential to the game. There should have been a higher cost for its ability, e.g. exert Frodo twice. On a partially related subject, Glamdring should have been an artifact and should have given +3 to Strength. Glamdring is the most powerful weapon in the book, more powerful than Anduril (Narsil). It was a weapon borne by the Elven king Turgon of Gondolin in the First Age, while Narsil was made by a dwarf named Telchar, smith of Norgod. <br />
<br />
2R32 Flaming Brand <br />
2C101 Filibert Bolger <br />
2R108 O Elbereth! Gilthoniel! <br />
The Nazgul were my first Shadow and my first foil deck was a Nazgul deck. I have played them for a very long time, until the emergence of the Last Alliance/Horn decks and later Archery/Choke decks made them virtually unplayable. Having in mind the book, Brand is definitely too strong, since the retreat of the Nazgul of Weathertop was caused more by Aragorn&#39;s valor than by the weapon he wielded (the Brand). However, Brand was a killer card only if combined with other strong cards, such as No strangers, Gondor Bowmen (choke decks), or Last Alliance and a sword (Elf-Gondor decks). Nazgul can already remove Brand (and O Elbereth!) via Stricken dumb. The solution is obvious. They need an efficient condition removal, which removes at least three FP conditions. This is logical, since the nazgul wield the Nine rings and therefore wield Sauron&#39;s sorcery (and condition removal is nothing but sorcery, or wizardry). This also removes O Elbereth!. O Elbereth is a card 100% in tune with the LOTR story - Frodo shouting Elbereth&#39;s name and taking of the Ring has saved his life and consequently all the Middle-Earth. Only a person who has never read LOTR could have made a decision to ban that card. <br />
<br />
1U108 No Stranger to the Shadows <br />
The problem with &quot;Cult. enf.&quot; with this card is caused by the fact that in the game Boromir and Arwen are Rangers. In reality, only Aragorn and Faramir (the one from the book, not the idiot from the movie) are rangers. However, the twilight denial strategy can be countered by an efficient condition removal, such as Saruman&#39;s Power. Almost all shadow cultures should get a condition removal, based on their expertise in sorcery (Uruk-hai with Saruman and Nazgul should have the best condition removal, then come the Mordor orcs and Moria Orcs (actually, the Balrog), then the Easterlings/Southrons (Discovered is OK) and the last place goes to Dunlendings - typical barbarians. <br />
<br />
3R38 Aragorn, Heir to the White City <br />
Aragorn needs to be extra-strong. It is clear to everyone who has read the book. Twilight denial decks can be countered by the condition removal, so what&#39;s the problem? <br />
<br />
3R42 Horn of Boromir <br />
This card doesn&#39;t fit the plot of tLOTR. The designers should have thought about it from day one. Now that its text is such as it is, you should leave it. Boromir can blow his horn all he wants, but it is to no avail against a good Moria swarm. <br />
<br />
THE END RESULT (I have not taken the new Shadow cultures and strategies from BOHD in account since I&#39;m not yet familiar with them): <br />
<br />
1. No more Elf-Gondor (Horn/Last Alliance) decks, no more decks that counted on twilight denial - Gondor decks in all shapes and sizes (archery-choke, rb rangers,...), no more Shoulder decks (as if there were any from the beginning). On a personal level, I am sorry that I won&#39;t be able to play my Gandalf Trust Me/Gondor deck which somewhat relies on the twilight denial and has won the last two tournaments I played on (including a large tournament with many international players). <br />
<br />
2. Nobody will play the Uruk-hai. Only the Uruk-hai archery and trackers will be playable (and it will need to have at least 2xGreed and 1xEnquea - see no. 3) <br />
<br />
3. Everybody will play the Nine companion decks, now that Saruman, Savagery and Nertea are gone. Everybody knows that fierce minions are the best remedy for large fellowships. Greed can be countered by the condition removal, Deep in Thought (Greed needs to spot twilight as does Deep in Thought) or Fortress Never Fallen. Enquea will at first kill common Eowyn. Only the second time it could do damage to an important companion. That leaves &quot;only&quot; seven companions to deal with. <br />
<br />
4. The Rohirrim have become the strongest Free peoples culture, especially in combination with Gondor, Gandalf or with Gondor and Gandalf. It is absurd that the Rohirrim are such a well rounded culture, they are strong in skirmishes, they have archery, they even have the possession and condition removal, as if they had wizards in their ranks. Condition removal should be reserved for Gandalf (the wizard and the Elves, who possess &quot;magical&quot; abilities derived from the nature itself). Who has ever heard of the Rohan archers? As the people, Rohirrim are inferior when compared to Gondorians (who are of Numenorian descent), not to mention the Elves and Gandalf (who is a Maia). In the game the Rohirrim are the most powerful. It contradicts the book. It almost seems that the Rohirrim are Maiar or even Valar <br />
<br />
5. The prevailing decks in the new format will be: <br />
a - Rohan-Gondor Help in Doubt and Need deck with nine companions. Common Eowyn against Enquea and Greed, Ithilien trap against Grima and Fortress Never Fallen against Greed (Greed will be played only by Uruk archery decks anyway). <br />
b - the extension of the above deck that includes Gandalf - the deck that cannot lose a skirmish - Gandalf/Rohan/Gondor (Help/Trust Me) deck. Ithilien trap takes care of the new Grima, Deep in Thought against Greed and Eowyn against Enquea. <br />
c- Dauntless Hunter deck with 9 companions (this deck is vulnerable against Dunland, once they have 3 sites and are fierce with Hillman horde on the table and against the Nazgul, who take out companions one by one). <br />
The first two decks are almost invincible. <br />
<br />
6. The shift in metagame to nine companion decks and the fact that Nertea is banned will make Moria inefficient. <br />
<br />
7. Dunland will profit from the disappearance of the choke decks, but Help and Help/Trust me decks are more than strong against them. <br />
<br />
8. Sauron pretty much stays the same. <br />
<br />
9. The shadow culture that profits the most from this are the Nazgul. Since there is no more choke, Nazgul decks will increase in the number of cards and will be able to fight the large fellowships. With no flaming brands, the Nazgul will actually win skirmishes (except against the Rohirrim in a and b deck under the number 5). <br />
<br />
10. and the most important: <br />
two things may happen: <br />
a - That this format becomes mandatory for all the sanctioned tournaments. This will result in a drop in the number of players. I would certainly stop buying the cards and so would a lot of other players I talked to. We would organize Open tournaments independently of Decipher and provide the awards ourselves. Many players would stop playing and collecting cards and it would be the beginning of the end of the LOTR tcg. <br />
b - That the game designers and other people working for Decipher hear the Vox populi and put the new format into a recycle bin where it belongs. Or at least, let the Open be the preferable format for all the Tournaments. <br />
<br />
The bottom line is, the bans will cause shift in the metagame, but the decks will become even less diverse then they were before.<br />
<br />
In the end, I would like to comment on Decipher&#39;s explanation why they have decided to ban cards instead of errating them (not to confuse the new, inexperienced and casual players). From where I stand, they should be concerned about confusing and losing the experienced players and collectors, who don&#39;t like the fact that the cards they have spent their money on aren&#39;t worth anything any more, who are aware of the fact that more cards could and will be added to the banned cards list and will lose their value accordingly. Once they realize which are the new power decks and cards that make them so powerful, they will ban on until nothing is left but Frodo and the (common) Ring. Errata can always be taught, explained and learned. Banning the cards outrages the players and collectors and drives them away from the game. <br />
